			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2019</a> paper:</span><br><i>Consistency management via a combination of triple graph grammars and linear programming</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/NilsBWeidmann.html">Nils B. Weidmann</a>, <a href="../profile/AnthonyAnjorin.html">Anthony Anjorin</a>, <a href="../profile/ErhanLeblebici.html">Erhan Leblebici</a>, <a href="../profile/AndySchürr.html">Andy Schürr</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3357766.3359544">10.1145/3357766.3359544</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagM">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s central topic is specifying or applying transformations (rewriting/mapping/synchronization).
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It includes substantial tool support or infrastructure relevant for engineering/using languages.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It emphasizes modularity/composition/integration (embedding or coordinating language components).
</li></ul></li></ul>
